  "text": "# Controller-Runtime Reconciliation Registration in Kubernetes\n\n## Overview\n\nKubernetes implements controller registration through a manager pattern defined in the kube-controller-manager. This architecture differs from the external controller-runtime library but follows similar principles.\n\n## Core Components\n\n### 1. Controller Interface (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controller_descriptor.go)\n\nThe fundamental interface that all controllers must implement:\n```go\ntype Controller interface {\n  Name() string\n  Run(context.Context)\n}\n```\n\nEvery controller registered with the manager must satisfy this interface with two methods:\n- **Name()**: Returns the canonical name of the controller\n- **Run(ctx context.Context)**: Executes the controller reconciliation loop; blocks until context is cancelled and ensures all goroutines are terminated before returning\n\n### 2. Controller Descriptor Pattern (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controller_descriptor.go)\n\nControllers are registered via descriptors that hold metadata and constructors:\n```go\ntype ControllerConstructor func(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, controllerName string) (Controller, error)\n\ntype ControllerDescriptor struct {\n  name                      string\n  constructor               ControllerConstructor\n  requiredFeatureGates      []featuregate.Feature\n  aliases                   []string\n  isDisabledByDefault       bool\n  isCloudProviderController bool\n  requiresSpecialHandling   bool\n}\n\nfunc (r *ControllerDescriptor) BuildController(ctx context.Context, controllerCtx ControllerContext) (Controller, error)\n```\n\nThe **BuildController()** method (line 93) invokes the ControllerConstructor, which creates and returns the actual Controller implementation.\n\n### 3. Manager Registration Flow (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go)\n\nThe main entry point **Run()** function (line 185) orchestrates the controller lifecycle:\n\n1. **BuildControllers()** (line 256) - Creates all controllers from their descriptors:\n   - Iterates through all ControllerDescriptors\n   - Calls BuildController() for each descriptor\n   - Collects controllers into a slice\n   - Registers health checkers and debug handlers\n\n2. **RunControllers()** (line 271) - Starts all controllers concurrently:\n   - Launches each controller in a separate goroutine\n   - Applies jitter to stagger controller startup\n   - Calls controller.Run(ctx) for each controller (line 722)\n   - Manages shutdown gracefully with timeouts\n\n### 4. Controller Loop Wrapper (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controller_utils.go)\n\nThe **controllerLoop** struct wraps actual controller implementations to conform to the Controller interface:\n```go\ntype controllerLoop struct {\n  name string\n  run  runFunc\n}\n\nfunc (loop *controllerLoop) Name() string {\n  return loop.name\n}\n\nfunc (loop *controllerLoop) Run(ctx context.Context) {\n  loop.run(ctx)\n}\n```\n\nThe **newControllerLoop()** function creates these wrappers, turning any runFunc into a Controller.\n\n### 5. Concrete Example: Namespace Controller\n\n#### Constructor (pkg/controller/namespace/namespace_controller.go, line 66)\n```go\nfunc NewNamespaceController(\n  ctx context.Context,\n  kubeClient clientset.Interface,\n  metadataClient metadata.Interface,\n  discoverResourcesFn func() ([]*metav1.APIResourceList, error),\n  namespaceInformer coreinformers.NamespaceInformer,\n  resyncPeriod time.Duration,\n  finalizerToken v1.FinalizerName) *NamespaceController\n```\n\nCreates the actual NamespaceController struct with:\n- A rate-limited work queue\n- Informer event handlers for namespace changes\n- A deletion handler for cleaning up namespace resources\n\n#### Reconciliation Loop (pkg/controller/namespace/namespace_controller.go, line 198)\n```go\nfunc (nm *NamespaceController) Run(ctx context.Context, workers int)\n```\n\nThe Run method:\n1. Waits for cache synchronization\n2. Spawns worker goroutines\n3. Each worker processes items from the queue indefinitely\n4. Synchronizes namespace state and handles finalizers\n5. Shuts down gracefully when context is cancelled\n\n#### Registration in Manager (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/core.go, line 669-680)\n\nThe namespace controller is registered through:\n```go\nnamespaceController := namespacecontroller.NewNamespaceController(...)\nreturn newControllerLoop(func(ctx context.Context) {\n  namespaceController.Run(ctx, int(controllerContext.ComponentConfig.NamespaceController.ConcurrentNamespaceSyncs))\n}, controllerName), nil\n```\n\nThis wraps the domain-specific NamespaceController with its Run method into a generic controllerLoop implementing the Controller interface.\n\n## Extended Interfaces (staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go)\n\nControllers can optionally implement additional interfaces:\n\n1. **Debuggable** - Provides HTTP debug handlers accessible at /debug/controllers/{controllerName}/\n2. **HealthCheckable** - Enables custom health checks exposed on the /healthz endpoint\n\n## Registration Chain Summary\n\n1. kube-controller-manager starts (controllermanager.Run)\n2. BuildControllers creates all registered controllers:\n   - Invokes ControllerDescriptor.BuildController\n   - Calls ControllerConstructor (e.g., newNamespaceController)\n   - Wraps result in controllerLoop\n3. RunControllers starts all controllers:\n   - Spawns goroutine for each controller\n   - Calls controller.Run(ctx)\n   - Namespace controller processes work queue until context cancellation\n4. Reconciliation loop continues until manager shutdown\n\nThis architecture separates domain-specific controller logic (pkg/controller/*) from manager infrastructure (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app), allowing clean composition and lifecycle management of multiple independent controllers within a single process."
}

